 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a user query as a JSON object with a single \"text\" field, for example:\n{\n  \"text\": \"<user query here>\"\n}\n\nYour task is to classify each query into exactly ONE category from the fixed set of intent categories listed below. Select only the single most relevant and specific category that accurately reflects the user's intent—never multiple categories, and never provide explanations or formatting. Your response should be the bare category label (lowercase, as given), and nothing else.\n\nIntent Categories (with domain-specific guidelines and nuanced distinctions):\n\n- alarm_query: For queries about existing alarms or alarm status (e.g., \"Do I have any alarms set?\", \"What alarms are on?\").\n- alarm_set: For requests to set a new alarm or change an alarm (e.g., \"Wake me at 7am\", \"Set an alarm for 8\").\n- calendar_set: For scheduling, creating, or modifying events or appointments (e.g., \"Add a meeting at 2pm\", \"Schedule a dentist appointment\").\n- calendar_remove: For removing or cancelling calendar events (e.g., \"Cancel my meeting at 3pm\").\n- calendar_query: For information about scheduled events (e.g., \"What's on my calendar today?\", \"Do I have plans this weekend?\").\n- cooking_recipe: For queries about food preparation or recipes (e.g., \"How do I make lasagna?\", \"Recipe for chicken curry\").\n- datetime_query: For questions about current date, time, or related info (e.g., \"What's the time?\", \"What day is it?\").\n- email_query: For searching, checking, or finding emails (e.g., \"Do I have new emails?\", \"Show unread emails from Sarah\").\n- email_sendemail: For composing or sending an email (e.g., \"Send an email to John\").\n- general_quirky: For jokes, playful commands, Easter eggs, and non-serious or banter responses that do NOT fit other categories (e.g., \"Tell me a joke\"). Note: If the user asks for a diary or record in an ambiguous or creative way (like \"record what happened today\") and does not clearly refer to a scheduled event, use general_quirky.\n- iot_hue_lightoff: For requests specifically about turning off Philips Hue lights (e.g., \"Turn off the living room lights\").\n- lists_createoradd: For creating a list, or adding items to a list (e.g., \"Add milk to my shopping list\", \"Start a new to-do list\").\n- lists_remove: For removing items from a list (e.g., \"Remove eggs from my grocery list\").\n- lists_query: For checking or viewing a list or its contents (e.g., \"What's on my packing list?\").\n- music_query: For seeking information about music, artists, songs, or genres (e.g., \"Who sings this song?\", \"Show me pop songs\").\n- news_query: For requesting news articles, recent happenings, or asking for news from a source or publication. Do NOT use for general fact, definition, or QA even if news-related (use appropriate QA category instead).\n- play_audiobook: For playing audiobooks (e.g., \"Play Harry Potter audiobook\").\n- play_music: For direct requests to play music (e.g., \"Play pop music\", \"Play my party playlist\").\n- play_podcasts: For direct requests to play podcasts (e.g., \"Play the latest episode of This American Life\").\n- play_radio: For playing radio stations (e.g., \"Play NPR radio\").\n- qa_currency: For questions about currency values and conversions (e.g., \"What's 10 dollars in euros?\").\n- qa_definition: For requests for word definitions (e.g., \"What does ephemeral mean?\").\n- qa_factoid: For requests for facts, trivia, general info, or factual data except those about definitions, currency, or stocks (e.g., \"Who is the president of France?\", \"How many people live in Canada?\").\n- qa_stock: For questions about stock prices or company stock information (e.g., \"What's the price of Tesla stock?\").\n- recommendation_events: For requests for recommended events to attend (e.g., \"What's happening this weekend?\").\n- recommendation_locations: For requests for recommended places, businesses, or locations to visit (e.g., \"Recommend a coffee shop nearby\").\n- takeaway_order: For ordering food to be delivered or picked up (e.g., \"Order pizza\", \"Get me sushi\").\n- social_post: For posting content to social media (e.g., \"Post on Twitter\").\n- transport_query: For directions, commute times, public transport info, or travel status (e.g., \"How do I get to the airport?\", \"Is the train delayed?\").\n- weather_query: For weather conditions or forecasts (e.g., \"What's the weather like tomorrow?\").\n\nDomain-specific Rules and Nuances:\n- For diary-like or journaling prompts (\"record what happened today\") that are not clearly asking to schedule a calendar event, use general_quirky (do NOT assume this is a calendar_set).\n- Never assign the same query to multiple categories or provide an explanation.\n- Choose the MOST SPECIFIC and relevant label; do not default to broader categories when a more precise one fits.\n- Always use the domain-specific categories as outlined (see music, news, calendar vs. alarm, etc.).\n- Make NO assumptions beyond the explicit content of the \"text\" field.\n\nYOUR OUTPUT: The single intent label as provided above, with no additional text, punctuation, or formatting."
 },
